INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Tableau Desktop user needs to combine rows from two quarterly sales tables that share identical column structures into a single dataset. Which Data Source page operation should they use?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Inner Join"},{"id":"b","text":"Relationship"},{"id":"c","text":"Union"},{"id":"d","text":"Data Blend"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material describes Unions as used to 'combine tables with same columns.' When two tables have identical column structures and you want to stack their rows, a Union is the correct operation. An Inner Join merges columns from two tables based on a matching key. A Relationship links tables at the logical layer using auto-aggregation. Data Blending combines data from separate connections via a linking field.$patch$, $patch$Connecting to and Preparing Data$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/union.htm","label":"Tableau — Union Your Data"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
