  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Tableau Desktop user wants to combine two CSV files that share identical column structures by stacking their rows into a single dataset. Which feature on the Data Source page should they use?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Join"},{"id":"b","text":"Blend"},{"id":"c","text":"Union"},{"id":"d","text":"Relationship"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Unions: combine tables with same columns.' Stacking rows from two identically structured CSV files is a Union operation. A Join combines tables horizontally on a key. A Blend merges data from separate connections via a linking field. A Relationship is a logical-layer connection between tables, not a row-stacking operation.$patch$, $patch$Connecting to and Preparing Data$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/union.htm","label":"Tableau Help – Union Your Data"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
