INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$In the Tableau Data Source page, a developer wants to stack two identically structured quarterly sales tables (Q1_Sales and Q2_Sales) into a single dataset. Which operation accomplishes this?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Join the tables using an Inner Join on the primary key"},{"id":"b","text":"Create a Relationship between the two tables"},{"id":"c","text":"Union the two tables"},{"id":"d","text":"Blend the two tables using a common dimension"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Unions: combine tables with same columns.' A Union appends rows from tables that share the same column structure, which is exactly what is needed to stack Q1 and Q2 sales data. A Join combines tables horizontally by matching keys — it does not stack rows. A Relationship is a logical-layer link for related tables, not for stacking identical structures. Data blending combines data from separate connections at the view level, not at the source level.$patch$, $patch$Connecting to and Preparing Data$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/union.htm","label":"Tableau – Union Your Data"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDS-C01-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$In the Tableau Data Source page, a developer wants to stack two identically structured quarterly sales tables (Q1_Sales and Q2_Sales) into a single dataset. Which operation accomplishes this?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$In Tableau Desktop, a field displayed as a green pill on the Measures shelf represents which combination of role and default behavior?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"A discrete dimension that creates column headers"},{"id":"b","text":"A continuous measure that is aggregated by default"},{"id":"c","text":"A discrete measure that produces individual marks"},{"id":"d","text":"A continuous dimension that creates an axis"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material describes: 'Measures (quantitative, green pill): aggregated by default (SUM/AVG/COUNT/etc)' and 'Continuous (green) vs Discrete (blue): affects axis type (continuous = axis, discrete = headers).' A green pill on the Measures shelf is therefore a continuous, quantitative field that Tableau aggregates by default. Blue pills represent discrete fields that produce headers. A discrete measure would appear as a blue pill, and a continuous dimension would still be shown on the Dimensions shelf.$patch$, $patch$Connecting to and Preparing Data$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/datafields_typesandroles_dataroles_dimensionmeasure.htm","label":"Tableau – Dimensions and Measures, Blue and Green"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDS-C01-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$In Tableau Desktop, a field displayed as a green pill on the Measures shelf represents which combination of role and default behavior?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Tableau analyst has sales data in a Salesforce connection and product cost data in a MySQL connection. No direct join is possible between the two sources. Which Tableau feature allows them to combine these two sources in a single view using a shared dimension?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Cross-database join"},{"id":"b","text":"Full Outer Join"},{"id":"c","text":"Data blending"},{"id":"d","text":"Wildcard union"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Data blending: combines data from multiple connections via linking field (typically dimension in common).' When a direct physical join between two different connections is not feasible, data blending uses a linking field to combine aggregated results from a secondary source into the primary source's view. A cross-database join physically merges tables from different connections and requires compatible join keys at the data source level. A Full Outer Join is a join type, not a multi-connection feature. A Wildcard union stacks files matching a name pattern.$patch$, $patch$Connecting to and Preparing Data$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/multiple_connections.htm","label":"Tableau – Blend Your Data"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDS-C01-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Tableau analyst has sales data in a Salesforce connection and product cost data in a MySQL connection. No direct join is possible between the two sources. Which Tableau feature allows them to combine these two sources in a single view using a shared dimension?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which Tableau filter type is evaluated FIRST in the order of operations, making it the foundation that all other filters must respect?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Dimension filter"},{"id":"b","text":"Measure filter"},{"id":"c","text":"Context filter"},{"id":"d","text":"Top N filter"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Context filters are evaluated first in Tableau's order of operations. Once a context filter is applied, all subsequent filters (dimension, measure, Top N, etc.) operate only on the data that passes through the context filter. This is why context filters are used as the 'foundation' for Top N or percentage-based filters. Dimension and measure filters run after context filters, so they cannot affect what the context filter has already restricted.$patch$, $patch$Exploring and Analyzing Data$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/filtering.htm","label":"Tableau Help — Filter Data from Your Views"},{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/filtering_context.htm","label":"Tableau Help — Add Context Filters"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDS-C01-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Which Tableau filter type is evaluated FIRST in the order of operations, making it the foundation that all other filters must respect?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A data analyst wants to combine two members of the 'Region' dimension — 'East' and 'West' — into a single category called 'Coastal'. Which Tableau feature should they use?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Set"},{"id":"b","text":"Group"},{"id":"c","text":"Parameter"},{"id":"d","text":"Calculated field using IF/THEN"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Groups in Tableau are used to statically combine dimension members into higher-level categories. In this scenario, selecting 'East' and 'West' and creating a group named 'Coastal' is the direct purpose of the Group feature. A Set is dynamic and typically used for in/out analysis based on conditions or Top N. A Parameter holds a single user-editable value and would require extra logic. A calculated field could achieve a similar result but is more complex and is not the purpose-built feature for simple member combining.$patch$, $patch$Exploring and Analyzing Data$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/sortgroup_groups_creating.htm","label":"Tableau Help — Group Your Data"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
