  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which Tableau file extension represents a packaged workbook that bundles both the workbook XML and a local data extract into a single file?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":".twb"},{"id":"b","text":".tds"},{"id":"c","text":".twbx"},{"id":"d","text":".hyper"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A .twbx file is a packaged workbook that contains both the workbook XML and any associated data extracts, making it self-contained and easy to share. By contrast, a .twb file is the raw XML workbook without any packaged data. A .tds file stores only the data source connection metadata, and .hyper is Tableau's in-memory extract format — not a workbook container. Source: 'File types: .twb (workbook XML), .twbx (packaged workbook with data extract).'$patch$, $patch$Understanding Tableau Concepts$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/environ_filesandfolders.htm","label":"Tableau File Types and Folders"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDS-C01-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Which Tableau file extension represents a packaged workbook that bundles both the workbook XML and a local data extract into a single file?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Tableau user wants to place a date field on the Columns shelf so that it renders as a continuous axis rather than discrete date-part headers. Which of the following best describes what determines this behavior in Tableau?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Whether the field is placed on Rows vs. Columns"},{"id":"b","text":"Whether the date field is set to continuous (green) or discrete (blue)"},{"id":"c","text":"Whether the field is a dimension or a measure"},{"id":"d","text":"Whether the data source is a live connection or an extract"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$In Tableau, continuous fields (shown in green) produce a numeric axis, while discrete fields (shown in blue) produce individual headers. Date fields specifically can be toggled between continuous and discrete: a continuous date creates a smooth date axis, whereas a discrete date breaks the view into labeled date-part headers (e.g., month names). The shelf placement, dimension/measure classification of other fields, and connection type do not control this behavior. Source: 'Continuous (green) vs Discrete (blue): Continuous fields create axes; discrete fields create headers. Date fields can be either: continuous (date axis) or discrete (date parts as headers).'$patch$, $patch$Understanding Tableau Concepts$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/datafields_typesandroles_dataroles_continuous.htm","label":"Tableau — Continuous and Discrete Fields"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDS-C01-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Tableau user wants to place a date field on the Columns shelf so that it renders as a continuous axis rather than discrete date-part headers. Which of the following best describes what determines this behavior in Tableau?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An organization needs employees to view Tableau workbooks without purchasing full Desktop licenses. The organization's data is sensitive and must NOT be shared publicly. Which Tableau product is the most appropriate free option for these read-only viewers?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Tableau Public"},{"id":"b","text":"Tableau Reader"},{"id":"c","text":"Tableau Bridge"},{"id":"d","text":"Tableau Prep Builder"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Tableau Reader is a free application that allows users to view packaged workbooks (.twbx) locally without publishing them anywhere. This satisfies the requirement of keeping data private. Tableau Public is also free but requires workbooks to be saved to the public web, which would expose sensitive data. Tableau Bridge is used to connect Tableau Cloud to on-premises data sources — it is not a viewer application. Tableau Prep Builder is a data preparation tool, not a viewer. Source: 'Tableau Reader (free viewer)' and 'Tableau Public is free but workbooks save to public web.'$patch$, $patch$Understanding Tableau Concepts$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://www.tableau.com/products/reader","label":"Tableau Reader Overview"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
