         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Heatmap"},{"id":"b","text":"Histogram"},{"id":"c","text":"Treemap"},{"id":"d","text":"Line chart"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material identifies the Histogram as the chart for 'distribution,' which groups continuous values into bins and shows frequency counts — exactly what is needed to understand how sales amounts are distributed across ranges. A heatmap shows density across two dimensions using color, a treemap shows hierarchical part-to-whole relationships, and a line chart shows trends over time.$patch$, $patch$Sharing Insights$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/buildexamples_histogram.htm","label":"Tableau — Build a Histogram"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDS-C01-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Tableau author needs to visualize the distribution of sales amounts across different ranges to understand the frequency of values. Which chart type is most appropriate?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$When publishing a workbook, which key difference distinguishes Tableau Cloud from Tableau Server?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Tableau Cloud supports only static image exports, while Tableau Server supports interactive views."},{"id":"b","text":"Tableau Cloud is a SaaS offering managed by Tableau, while Tableau Server is self-hosted by the organization."},{"id":"c","text":"Tableau Cloud requires Tableau Desktop, while Tableau Server supports Tableau Public only."},{"id":"d","text":"Tableau Cloud is free for all users, while Tableau Server requires a paid license."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states: 'Tableau Cloud (SaaS) vs Tableau Server (self-hosted).' This is the fundamental architectural distinction — Tableau Cloud is fully managed by Tableau/Salesforce as a Software-as-a-Service product, while Tableau Server is installed and maintained on infrastructure owned or managed by the customer's organization. The other options contain incorrect statements not supported by the source material.$patch$, $patch$Sharing Insights$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/online/en-us/to_tableau_online.htm","label":"Tableau — Tableau Cloud Overview"},{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/server/en-us/get_started_server.htm","label":"Tableau — Tableau Server Overview"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDS-C01-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$When publishing a workbook, which key difference distinguishes Tableau Cloud from Tableau Server?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An author opens the Show Me panel in Tableau Desktop and notices that one chart type appears in bold. What does the bold formatting indicate?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The chart type is unavailable for the selected fields."},{"id":"b","text":"The chart type is Tableau's recommended option for the selected fields."},{"id":"c","text":"The chart type was most recently used in the workbook."},{"id":"d","text":"The chart type requires an additional license to use."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Show Me menu: suggests chart types based on selected fields; bolded = recommended.' Bold formatting in the Show Me panel indicates that Tableau considers that chart type the best match for the combination of fields currently selected. It does not indicate unavailability, recent usage, or a licensing requirement.$patch$, $patch$Sharing Insights$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/buildmanual_shelves_showme.htm","label":"Tableau — Show Me — Changing the View Type"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDS-C01-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An author opens the Show Me panel in Tableau Desktop and notices that one chart type appears in bold. What does the bold formatting indicate?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Tableau analyst saves a workbook and wants to share it with a colleague who has no Tableau installation. The colleague only needs to view the data — not edit anything. Which file format should the analyst use so the colleague can open the packaged workbook along with its data extract?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":".twb"},{"id":"b","text":".tds"},{"id":"c","text":".twbx"},{"id":"d","text":".hyper"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$According to the source material, a .twbx file is a 'packaged workbook with data extract,' meaning it bundles both the workbook XML and the underlying data into a single file that can be opened by Tableau Reader (which is free). A .twb file contains only the workbook XML and requires a live connection or separately provided data. A .tds file is a data source connection file, not a workbook. A .hyper file is Tableau's raw extract format and cannot be opened as a standalone workbook.$patch$, $patch$Understanding Tableau Concepts$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/environ_filesandfolders.htm","label":"Tableau File Types and Folders — Tableau Desktop and Web Authoring Help"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDS-C01-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Tableau analyst saves a workbook and wants to share it with a colleague who has no Tableau installation. The colleague only needs to view the data — not edit anything. Which file format should the analyst use so the colleague can open the packaged workbook along with its data extract?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$In Tableau's order of operations, which filter type is applied FIRST before all others?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Context filters"},{"id":"b","text":"Data source filters"},{"id":"c","text":"Extract filters"},{"id":"d","text":"Dimension filters"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states the Tableau order of operations as: 'Extract filters → Data source filters → Context filters → FIXED LODs → Dimension filters → INCLUDE/EXCLUDE LODs → Measure filters → Table calcs.' Extract filters are applied first because they limit the data that is pulled into the extract itself, before any other filter type can act on the data. Context filters come third, and dimension filters come fifth in this sequence.$patch$, $patch$Understanding Tableau Concepts$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/order_of_operations.htm","label":"Tableau Order of Operations — Tableau Desktop and Web Authoring Help"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDS-C01-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$In Tableau's order of operations, which filter type is applied FIRST before all others?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Tableau developer places a date field on the Columns shelf and it renders as a continuous green pill, producing a date axis along the bottom of the view. What behavior would change if the developer converted that same date field to a discrete blue pill?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The field would be removed from the view entirely and placed in the Filters shelf."},{"id":"b","text":"Tableau would automatically aggregate the field as a measure instead of a dimension."},{"id":"c","text":"The continuous date axis would be replaced by discrete date part headers."},{"id":"d","text":"The date field would convert to a .hyper extract format for faster rendering."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Continuous fields create axes; discrete fields create headers' and 'Date fields can be either: continuous (date axis) or discrete (date parts as headers).' Converting the date pill from green (continuous) to blue (discrete) changes the visual encoding from a continuous date axis to discrete headers representing date parts (e.g., individual years or months shown as column headers). The other options are not described behaviors related to this conversion.$patch$, $patch$Understanding Tableau Concepts$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/datafields_typesandroles_datefield.htm","label":"Discrete and Continuous Fields — Tableau Desktop and Web Authoring Help"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDS-C01-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Tableau developer places a date field on the Columns shelf and it renders as a continuous green pill, producing a date axis along the bottom of the view. What behavior would change if the developer converted that same date field to a discrete blue pill?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An organization uses Tableau Cloud (SaaS) but its primary database is hosted on an on-premises server behind a corporate firewall. Which Tableau product allows Tableau Cloud to maintain a live or scheduled connection to that on-premises data source?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Tableau Prep Conductor"},{"id":"b","text":"Tableau Bridge"},{"id":"c","text":"Tableau Reader"},{"id":"d","text":"Tableau Prep Builder"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly identifies 'Tableau Bridge' as the product that 'keeps Cloud connected to on-prem data sources.' Tableau Prep Conductor handles server-side scheduling of Prep flows. Tableau Reader is a free viewer application. Tableau Prep Builder is a data preparation tool used for cleaning and shaping data. None of those three products are designed to bridge Tableau Cloud to on-premises databases.$patch$, $patch$Understanding Tableau Concepts$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/online/en-us/qs_connect_live_tableau_bridge.htm","label":"About Tableau Bridge — Tableau Cloud Help"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDS-C01-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An organization uses Tableau Cloud (SaaS) but its primary database is hosted on an on-premises server behind a corporate firewall. Which Tableau product allows Tableau Cloud to maintain a live or scheduled connection to that on-premises data source?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$When designing a Tableau dashboard, a best practice derived from visual design principles is to place the most important information in a specific area of the layout. Based on common reading pattern guidance, where should the highest-priority content be positioned?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Bottom-right corner, because users finish reading there and retain the last item seen."},{"id":"b","text":"Center of the dashboard, so it is equidistant from all edges."},{"id":"c","text":"Top-left area, following the F or Z reading pattern where the eye naturally starts."},{"id":"d","text":"Bottom-left corner, to anchor the dashboard and draw the eye downward."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Dashboard layout: F or Z reading pattern; most important info top-left.' Both the F-pattern and Z-pattern describe how Western readers naturally begin scanning content at the top-left of a page or screen. Placing the most critical KPIs or charts in that position maximizes the chance that viewers notice them immediately. Placing key information in the center, bottom-right, or bottom-left contradicts this established visual best practice.$patch$, $patch$Understanding Tableau Concepts$patch$,
         2, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/dashboards_best_practices.htm","label":"Dashboard Design Best Practices — Tableau Help"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDS-C01-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$When designing a Tableau dashboard, a best practice derived from visual design principles is to place the most important information in a specific area of the layout. Based on common reading pattern guidance, where should the highest-priority content be positioned?$patch$);

