  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$When designing a Tableau dashboard, a developer wants to apply the recommended layout principle so that the most critical information is placed where viewers' eyes naturally land first. According to Tableau visual best practices, where should this information be positioned?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Bottom-right corner of the dashboard"},{"id":"b","text":"Center of the dashboard"},{"id":"c","text":"Top-left area of the dashboard"},{"id":"d","text":"Bottom-left corner of the dashboard"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material notes: 'Dashboard layout: F or Z reading pattern; most important info top-left.' Both the F-pattern and Z-pattern describe how Western readers scan content — starting at the top-left. Placing key KPIs, titles, or primary charts in the top-left ensures they are seen first. Bottom-right, center, and bottom-left positions receive significantly less immediate visual attention.$patch$, $patch$Understanding Tableau Concepts$patch$,
