  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Tableau analyst wants to combine sales data from a MySQL database with budget data from a separate Excel file without creating a single merged data source. Which Tableau technique allows them to link these two separate connections using a common dimension field?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Cross-database join"},{"id":"b","text":"Union"},{"id":"c","text":"Data blending"},{"id":"d","text":"Relationship"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material defines 'Data blending: combines data from multiple connections via linking field (typically dimension in common).' It is specifically designed for linking separate connections at the viz level rather than merging them into one source. A cross-database join merges sources at the physical layer, a Union stacks rows with the same structure, and a Relationship connects tables within a single logical data source.$patch$, $patch$Connecting to and Preparing Data$patch$,
