  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$When a Top N filter is applied WITHOUT first adding a context filter, what unintended result may occur when used alongside a dimension filter?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The Top N filter will be completely ignored by Tableau"},{"id":"b","text":"The Top N ranking may be computed across the full dataset before the dimension filter is applied, returning fewer than N results in the view"},{"id":"c","text":"The dimension filter automatically becomes a context filter"},{"id":"d","text":"The measure filter overrides the Top N filter"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material notes that context filters restrict the data that subsequent filters act upon. Without a context filter, a Top N filter calculates its ranking against the entire dataset. When a separate dimension filter is then applied, it may exclude some of the top-ranked marks, resulting in fewer than N items appearing in the view — the classic 'Top N problem.' Making the dimension filter a context filter ensures Top N ranks only within the already-filtered subset. The other options describe behaviors that do not reflect how Tableau's filter order of operations works.$patch$, $patch$Exploring and Analyzing Data$patch$,
         1, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/filtering.htm","label":"Tableau Help – Filter Data from Your Views (Context Filters and Top N)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
