  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which of the following BEST describes the key difference between Tableau Public and Tableau Desktop?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Tableau Public supports private workbooks and more data connectors, while Tableau Desktop only saves to the public web"},{"id":"b","text":"Tableau Desktop is free and saves workbooks to a public website, while Tableau Public is a paid product"},{"id":"c","text":"Tableau Public is free but saves workbooks to the public web, while Tableau Desktop is paid and supports private workbooks plus more connectors"},{"id":"d","text":"Tableau Public and Tableau Desktop are identical products offered at different price points"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Tableau Public is free but workbooks save to public web; Desktop is paid and supports private workbooks plus more connectors.' This means anyone can view workbooks published from Tableau Public, which makes it unsuitable for sensitive or proprietary data. Tableau Desktop requires a paid license but offers privacy and a broader range of data connectors. The other options reverse or misrepresent these facts.$patch$, $patch$Understanding Tableau Concepts$patch$,
         1, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/getstarted_tableau_desktop.htm","label":"Tableau Public vs Tableau Desktop — Tableau Official Help"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'ANALYTICS-101-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Which of the following BEST describes the key difference between Tableau Public and Tableau Desktop?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$When building a dashboard, Tableau visual best practices recommend placing the most important information in which area of the layout to align with natural reading patterns?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Bottom-right corner, so it is the last thing the viewer sees"},{"id":"b","text":"Center of the dashboard, to draw equal attention from all sides"},{"id":"c","text":"Top-left area, to align with the F or Z reading pattern"},{"id":"d","text":"Bottom-left corner, following a reverse reading pattern"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material advises: 'Dashboard layout: F or Z reading pattern; most important info top-left.' Both the F-pattern and Z-pattern research in UX design show that viewers naturally begin scanning a page from the top-left. Placing key insights there ensures they receive the most attention. Positioning critical content in the center, bottom-right, or bottom-left conflicts with these established reading patterns.$patch$, $patch$Understanding Tableau Concepts$patch$,
         1, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/performance_tips.htm","label":"Best Practices for Designing Efficient Workbooks — Tableau Official Documentation"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'ANALYTICS-101-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$When building a dashboard, Tableau visual best practices recommend placing the most important information in which area of the layout to align with natural reading patterns?$patch$);

